# Family CFO — persisted deploy/patch destination.
#
# Copy to `.deploy.env` (gitignored) and fill in. Both scripts/deploy.sh and
# scripts/patch.sh load it automatically, so `scripts/patch.sh web` goes to the
# right box without you retyping the address every time — and, more importantly,
# without it silently falling back to patching the machine you're sitting at.
#
# A real environment variable ALWAYS wins over this file, so a one-off still
# works:  SSH_HOST=other-box scripts/patch.sh web
#
# This file holds a destination, not a secret — but it is gitignored anyway,
# because a checkout should not carry someone else's home network in it.

# The box that hosts the containers. Several may be listed, space- or
# comma-separated, and are patched in order:  SSH_HOST="box1 box2"
SSH_HOST=192.168.1.10

# NOTE there is deliberately no TARGET here. local-vs-remote is derived from
# WHERE YOU ARE: if SSH_HOST is this machine (you're on the Linux box) the stack
# is patched locally; if it isn't (you're on the MacBook) it goes over SSH. The
# same file is therefore correct on both machines, and a stale TARGET can't send
# a patch somewhere you didn't mean. Set TARGET=local|remote only to force it.

# --- Authentication: there is NONE here, on purpose --------------------------
#
# NEVER put a password in this file. Nothing in this repo should hold a
# credential, and these scripts are built so none is needed.
#
# The right way is a ~/.ssh/config block, so `SSH_HOST` above can be a bare
# alias and ssh works out the rest:
#
#     Host family-cfo-box
#         HostName 192.168.1.10
#         User your-login
#         IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
#         IdentitiesOnly yes
#
#     # then:  SSH_HOST=family-cfo-box
#
# Authorise the key once, from YOUR terminal (this is the only time a password is
# typed, and it goes straight to ssh — never to a script or a config file):
#
#     ssh-copy-id -i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub your-login@192.168.1.10
#
# After that it is key-only, and a passphrase-protected key is unlocked once per
# session by ssh-agent.
#
# The three below are OPTIONAL ESCAPE HATCHES for a host you have no ~/.ssh/config
# entry for. Leave them unset and ssh resolves user/port/key itself.
# SSH_USER=
# SSH_PORT=
# SSH_KEY=

# Where the checkout lives on the box.
REMOTE_DIR=~/family-cfo

# --- iPhone (scripts/deploy-ios.sh) ------------------------------------------
# The phone is DISCOVERED, not declared, so it needs nothing here when only one
# device is connected. Set this only if you routinely have several paired:
# IOS_DEVICE=Alex's iPhone

# --- iOS builds (only if you deploy the iPhone app) --------------------------
#
# Your Apple Developer Team id. It is deliberately NOT committed (the Xcode
# project ships with an empty DEVELOPMENT_TEAM, ADR 0030); scripts/deploy-ios*.sh
# inject it at build time. Find it at https://developer.apple.com/account →
# Membership. Example shape (10 chars): ABCDE12345.
# IOS_TEAM_ID=YOUR_TEAM_ID

# --- TestFlight (scripts/release-testflight.sh) ------------------------------
#
# App Store Connect API key so the release script can upload without a browser.
# Create it once at App Store Connect -> Users and Access -> Integrations ->
# App Store Connect API -> generate a key. The role MUST be **Admin** — a lower
# role can't cloud-sign and fails with "Cloud signing permission error" (ADR
# 0035). Download the AuthKey_XXXX.p8 ONCE, keep it OUTSIDE the repo, and point
# ASC_KEY_PATH at it. The .p8 is a secret and is never committed; only its path
# lives here. IMPORTANT: ASC_KEY_ID must equal the key id in the .p8 filename
# (Apple names it AuthKey_<KEYID>.p8) — a mismatch yields a 401.
# ASC_KEY_ID=XXXXXXXXXX
# ASC_ISSUER_ID=xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx
# ASC_KEY_PATH=~/.appstoreconnect/private_keys/AuthKey_XXXXXXXXXX.p8
